Identifying Drivers of Expense Inequity Between Women’s and Men’s Collegiate Basketball

Cameron Jester

05/02/2022

The New York Times, Michelle Kondrich

Introduction

Hello! Welcome to my project that will outline the data science pipeline, which includes data wrangling/transformation, exploratory analysis, data visualizations, and creating predictive models. I have chosen to use the Collegiate Sports Budget data set from the tidytuesday Github repository. The files can be accessed here. This data set includes information for 38 collegiate sports across roughly 130,000 schools in the United States.

Expense inequity is an important topic to discuss when working with collegiate sports. The differences in expenditures between men’s and women’s sports teams can be the difference between a winning or losing season. During the 2020 March Madness competition, a 28 second video clip was released by Sedona Price of the University of Oregon Duck’s. The clip showed the men’s basketball workout facility, which included several weight stations, and state-of-the-art equipment, compared to the singular rack of weights for an entire women’s team. The video sparked meaningful discuss of parity across collegiate sports. One main argument for expenditure for men’s teams being proportional to those of women’s is that women’s teams do not bring in as much revenue. As a former basketball player, advocate for women’s equality, and passionate sports fan, I am diving into the data to see which factors are the most influential drivers of expense inequity between men’s and women’s collegiate basketball.

Exploratory Data Analysis

My first step of identifying the drivers of expense inequities is to clean, wrangle, and transform my data set into a compatible table to work with. To begin this stage, I filtered for “Basketball” under the ‘sports’ column, which condensed the data to exactly 10,000 schools. I made extensive use of the ‘dplyr’ package by mutating the data to create the following percentages for both the men and women’s teams:

-Participation

-Expenditures

-Revenue

Then, to aid with the visualization process, I made the table ‘wide’ by using the pivot_longer() function. Once I used the mutate functions, and the data table was wide, I had 160,000 pieces of information to analyze!

Machine learning

As mentioned in the Introduction, one of the arguments supporting the gap in expense between men’s and women’s basketball teams is the amount of revenue the respective teams bring in. While there is no dispute on whether that is true (Men’s March Madness generated $1.8 billion which compares to Women’s $34 million ) , using machine learning may help us determine if that is the only major indicator of expenditures.

set.seed(0510)
womens_split = initial_split(womens_basketball, prop = 0.7)
womens_train = training(womens_split)
womens_test = testing(womens_split)

mens_split = initial_split(mens_basketball, prop = 0.7)
mens_train = training(mens_split)
mens_test = testing(mens_split)

To begin the modeling process, the data had to be split into men’s and women’s tables. Then, training and testing sets were created for both tables, which were used to fit multiple regression models. Following the fitting process came predicting values and calculating an rMSE for each model.

lm_womens_fit = lm_spec %>%
  fit(exp_women ~ rev_women  + ef_female_count + partic_women + women_percent_partic   + women_percent_rev , data = womens_train)


lm_pred_test_womens = lm_womens_fit %>%
  predict(new_data = womens_test)


womens_test %>%

Cross-Validation

Based off of the rMSEs for the two models, it can be determined that the multiple regression model better predicted the expenditure for women’s teams, whereas the decision tree better predicted the expenditure for the men’s teams. Before we can dive into the reasons why each team takes to a different model, it would be a good idea to confirm if our two training sets can be trusted and effecitively used in our analysis.

The rmse for the women’s training set for the decision tree is: 334969.0

The rmse for the men’s training set for the decision tree is: 565084.7

The two rmse’s for each team’s training set are very similar to those which were obtained from their respective tree models. This means that the training sets for both teams will not lead to overfitting in our models! Therefore, we can use the decision trees to determine the drivers of expense inequity between men’s and women’s collegiate basketball.

Conclusions

You may have noticed that the men and women’s decision trees looks a bit different. The women’s tree includes 2 features (revenue and percentage of total revenue), with more branches, whereas the men’s tree only splits on one feature (revenue).

The following features were not included in either tree:

-ef_male_count/ef_female_count

-partic_men/partic_women

-men_partic_percent/women_partic_percent

Decision trees use an algorithm that determines which features are most prominent to the target, which in this case is the expenditure for teams. This means that from 2015-2019, the biggest factor in determining expenditures for men’s basketball teams was dependent on how much revenue they brought in. ‘Men_percent_rev’ was likely not added to the men’s tree as for most schools men’s teams generate much higher revenues, so the few schools where that was not the case, did not impact the model enough. Conversely, for schools in which their women’s team generated a higher revenue had an impact on the model.

Let’s not forget that for the women’s models multiple regression had a lower rMSE than the decision tree. Let’s take a look at which features had the biggest impact in the regression model:

lm_womens_fit

##         partic_women  women_percent_partic     women_percent_rev  
##            4.322e+03             2.207e+06            -3.257e+06

In this linear model, all other features held constant, the average expenditure for women’s basketball teams was $20300.0, which could be used for things such as uniforms, court time, and travel for games. For every $1 dollar increase of revenue, there is a decrease in expenditure of roughly .82 cents. As the number of female students increased by 1, there was a 30.62 increase in expenditure, similarly, as the number of women who participated on the basketball team increased by 1, roughly $500 was added to the expenditure. The following features are of percentages of the total between men and women’s teams. As women’s participation increased 1% of the total, there was an associated increase of $60,840, and as women’s revenue increased by 1%, there was an associated decrease of $9,361,000.

Overall, the models created suggest that revenue is the largest factor of expenditure for men’s basketball teams, yet it is not the only factor for women’s basketball. The other indicators of women’s expenditures include the total number of women attending each school, furthermore the total number of women participating in basketball, and the percentages of revenue and participation when compared to men’s averages. Determining expenditure for each team on a different set of factors increases expense inequity in college basketball.
